The '''Tochi Expedition''' was a punitive visit by Anglo-Indian troops to the [[Tochi Valley]] in 1897 to put down a rebellion there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/66527718|title=The Tochi trouble|publisher=The Inquirer & Commercial News|date=30 July 1897|accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref>

The rebellion started with an attack by the Madda Khel section of the [[Wazir (Pashtun tribe)|Waziris]] in June 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/riflebrigadechr02owngoog#page/n130/mode/2up|title=The Rifle Brigade Chronicle|page=113|accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref> 

The Tochi Valley Field Force assembed in response was commanded by General Corrie Bird<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/riflebrigadechr02owngoog#page/n130/mode/2up|title=The Rifle Brigade Chronicle|page=121|accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref> and included the 1st Brigade under the command of Brigadier-General [[Charles Egerton (Indian Army officer)|Charles Egerton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/riflebrigadechr02owngoog#page/n130/mode/2up|title=The Rifle Brigade Chronicle|page=124|accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref> The rebellion was finally put down in October 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/riflebrigadechr02owngoog#page/n130/mode/2up|title=The Rifle Brigade Chronicle|page=133|accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref>

==Resources==
* G.V. Kemball, Operations of the Tochi Field Force in 1897-98.  Simla, Govt. Central Printing Office (1900).

